.planning/phases/03-numpress-linear-mz/RESEARCH-port.md:213:### 4.2 Will We Match `small.numpress.mzpeak` Byte-for-Byte?
.planning/phases/03-numpress-linear-mz/RESEARCH-port.md:215:**Depends on the fixed-point selection in the Rust mzpeak writer.**
.planning/phases/03-numpress-linear-mz/RESEARCH-port.md:217:The reference mzpeak file was created by the Rust `mzpeak_prototyping` tool using `numpress-rs`. If it uses `optimal_linear_fixed_point` (which it should), then:
.planning/phases/03-numpress-linear-mz/RESEARCH-port.md:218:- **Input data:** The m/z array from `small.RAW` → fixed point calculation.
.planning/phases/03-numpress-linear-mz/RESEARCH-port.md:219:- **Rust numpress-rs:** encodes m/z with that fixed point → bytes in `mz_numpress_linear_bytes` column.
.planning/phases/03-numpress-linear-mz/RESEARCH-port.md:220:- **Our C#:** Given the same m/z array and computed fixed point, should produce **identical bytes**.
.planning/phases/03-numpress-linear-mz/RESEARCH-port.md:222:**Practical approach:** Extract the m/z from `small.numpress.mzpeak`, re-encode with our C# implementation, and assert byte-identity for at least the first chunk.
.planning/phases/03-numpress-linear-mz/RESEARCH-port.md:226:**From pynumpress docstring:** "Empirically accurate to at least 0.002 ppm."
.planning/phases/03-numpress-linear-mz/RESEARCH-port.md:228:**More precisely:** The fixed-point precision is 5 decimal places (10^−5), so the quantization error per value is ~0.5 × 10^−5. For m/z ~100–1000, this is:
.planning/phases/03-numpress-linear-mz/RESEARCH-port.md:230:- Practical error (in pynumpress testing): <0.002 ppm ≈ <0.0000002 relative.
.planning/phases/03-numpress-linear-mz/RESEARCH-port.md:232:**L∞ bound for round-trip:** |value[i] − decode(encode(value[i]))| ≤ 2×10^−5 (conservative).
