   148	    The prose in RESEARCH-port.md section 1 mis-describes the algorithm (it says least-squares slope and 5-byte
   149	    values / continuation-varint nibbles) — that prose is WRONG and MUST be ignored. The canonical facts below
   150	    are authoritative.
   151	
   152	    - OptimalLinearFixedPoint(double[]) is MAX-VALUE based (NOT least-squares): seed maxDouble = max(data[0],data[1]);
   153	      for i>=2, extrapol = data[i-1] + (data[i-1]-data[i-2]), diff = data[i]-extrapol,
   154	      maxDouble = max(maxDouble, ceil(abs(diff)+1)); return floor(0x7FFFFFFF / maxDouble).
   155	      dataSize==0 -> 0; dataSize==1 -> floor(0x7FFFFFFF / data[0]).
   156	    - EncodeLinear(double[], double fp): bytes 0-7 = fp as a BIG-ENDIAN IEEE-754 double (encodeFixedPoint);
   157	      then data[0] and data[1] each as a 4-byte LITTLE-ENDIAN int32 = (long)(value*fp + 0.5) (bytes 8-11, 12-15,
   158	      LSB first); then for i>=2: predicted = ints[1] + (ints[1]-ints[0]) on the QUANTIZED ints,
   159	      diff = (int)(quant[i] - predicted), encoded via encodeInt's 4-bit half-byte scheme starting at byte 16,
   160	      two half-bytes packed per byte, trailing odd half-byte flushed as (hb<<4). EncodeLinear(double[]) overload
   161	      computes fp via OptimalLinearFixedPoint internally. (NOTE: values are 4-byte int32, NOT 5-byte.)
   162	    - encodeInt/decodeInt: the canonical half-byte (nibble) scheme — head nibble encodes leading-zero count
   163	      (0..8) or, for the 0xf0000000 case, leading-ones count + 8; remaining nibbles carry the value low-to-high.
   164	      Port the bit loops EXACTLY from the reference (mask 0xf0000000, the init==0 / init==mask / else branches).
   165	    - DecodeLinear(byte[]) reconstructs the array, mirroring the reference (read BE-double fp; first two as 4-byte
   166	      LE int32 / fp; then extrapolate quantized ints and add decoded diff, divide by fp). dataSize==8 -> empty;
   167	      dataSize<8 -> throw; dataSize==12 -> 1 value. Round-trip max|Δ| <= 0.5/fp.
   168	    - Edge cases: empty array -> 8-byte (fp-only) output and decode -> empty; single value (12 bytes); two values
   169	      (16 bytes, no residuals); ascending m/z slices of length 1..N.
   170	    - EXACT VERIFICATION VECTORS (all MUST pass, byte-for-byte where stated):
   171	      (V1) OptimalLinearFixedPoint([1.0,2.0,3.0]) == 1073741823 (== floor(0x7FFFFFFF / 2)).
   172	      (V2) data=[100.0,100.5,101.0,101.5], fp=21367996 -> the canonical ms-numpress encode bytes are EXACTLY
   173	           (17 bytes, verified vs pynumpress 0.0.9): 41 74 60 CB C0 00 00 00 70 F9 5C 7F CE FF FF 7F 88.
   174	           Assert our EncodeLinear == these literal bytes (hardcode them — do NOT derive from pynumpress, to
   175	           avoid a circular oracle). decode(encode) is exact.
