   178	           m/z (after caller anchor-alignment, Task 2/4) is within 0.5/10599266 of the row's mz_chunk_start anchor.
   179	      (V4) BYTE-IDENTITY at a shared fp, asserted TWICE: our EncodeLinear(data, fp) bytes ==
   180	           (a) the known ms-numpress reference test-vector bytes for that data+fp, AND
   181	           (b) pynumpress.encode_linear(data, fp) bytes. This is byte-identity, NOT merely decode-within-bound.
   182	    - Cross-check vs pynumpress (python3.11, Ignore if absent): in addition to V4 byte-identity, assert
   183	      pynumpress.decode_linear(our-C#-bytes) is within 0.5/fp, and OptimalLinearFixedPoint matches
   184	      pynumpress.optimal_linear_fixed_point on real m/z slices. CAVEAT: pynumpress 0.0.9's decode_linear
   185	      REJECTS a 12-byte single-value stream (canonical source returns 1 value) — for the single-value-chunk
   186	      edge test use OUR DecodeLinear (canonical behavior) as the oracle, NOT pynumpress.
   187	    - phantom-leading-value: anchor decode to chunk start/end is the CALLER's concern (Task 2/4 test); the codec
   188	      returns the raw MSNumpress decode. Document the artifact in the codec header note (no harness/phase wording).
   189	  </behavior>
