   261	
   262	## 6. C# Implementation Plan
   263	
   264	### 6.1 File Structure
   265	
   266	**Target:** `ThermoRawFileParser/Writer/MzPeak/MSNumpress.cs`
   267	
   268	**Content (estimated ~200 lines):**
   269	```csharp
   270	using System;
   271	using System.Collections.Generic;
   272	
   273	namespace ThermoRawFileParser.Writer
   274	{
   275	    public static class MSNumpress
   276	    {
   277	        // Constants
   278	        private const int NUMPRESS_LINEAR_FIXED_POINT_MASS = 21367996; // Example scale
   279	        
   280	        // Public API
   281	        public static byte[] EncodeLinear(double[] data)
   282	        {
   283	            long fixedPoint = OptimalLinearFixedPoint(data);
   284	            return EncodeLinear(data, fixedPoint);
   285	        }
   286	        
   287	        public static byte[] EncodeLinear(double[] data, long fixedPoint)
   288	        {
   289	            // 1. Encode fixed point as 8 bytes (big-endian, via double bitcast)
   290	            // 2. Encode first two values as 5-byte fixed-point ints
   291	            // 3. Encode residuals via 4-bit varint scheme
   292	        }
   293	        
   294	        public static double[] DecodeLinear(byte[] encoded)
   295	        {
   296	            // Mirror of EncodeLinear
   297	        }
   298	        
   299	        public static long OptimalLinearFixedPoint(double[] data)
   300	        {
   301	            // Least-squares fit to find optimal scale
   302	        }
   303	        
   304	        // Helper: encodeInt / decodeInt for 4-bit half-byte residuals
   305	        private static int EncodeInt(long value, byte[] buffer, int offset) { ... }
   306	        private static long DecodeInt(byte[] buffer, ref int offset) { ... }
   307	    }
   308	}
   309	```
   310	
   311	### 6.2 Key Implementation Notes
   312	
   313	1. **Big-endian fixed point:** Store as `BitConverter.DoubleToInt64Bits(fixedPoint)` interpreted as BE. (C# BitConverter is LE-native, so explicit byte-swap needed.)
   314	2. **5-byte integer encoding:** Pack the first two quantized values as 5 bytes each (bytes 8–12, 13–17), using a helper to write 40-bit ints.
   315	3. **4-bit half-byte packing:** The residual encoding uses a custom bitstream (continuation bit in bit 3 of each nibble). Reference C++ uses a clever bit-unpacking loop; C# should mirror it exactly.
   316	4. **No dependencies:** Use only `System` namespace. No external libraries.
   317	
   318	### 6.3 Testing
   319	
   320	Unit tests in `MzPeakChunkTests.cs`:
   321	```csharp
   322	[Test]
   323	public void MSNumpressLinearRoundTrip()
   324	{
   325	    double[] data = { 100.0, 100.5, 101.0, 101.5, 102.0 };
   326	    byte[] encoded = MSNumpress.EncodeLinear(data);
   327	    double[] decoded = MSNumpress.DecodeLinear(encoded);
   328	    
   329	    for (int i = 0; i < data.Length; i++)
   330	    {
   331	        Assert.AreEqual(data[i], decoded[i], 1e-8);
   332	    }
   333	}
   334	
   335	[Test]
   336	public void MSNumpressLinearPyNumPressCompatibility()
   337	{
   338	    // Run pynumpress on the same data, compare encoded bytes
   339	}
   340	```
