   373	
   374	## 8. Decision: Vendor vs. External Dependency
   375	
   376	### 8.1 Recommended Decision: Vendor as Source File
   377	
   378	| Criterion | Verdict |
   379	|-----------|---------|
   380	| **License compatibility** | ✓ Apache-2.0 compatible with MIT |
   381	| **Size & complexity** | ✓ ~200 lines, no external deps |
   382	| **Maintainability** | ✓ Minimal; algorithm is stable (ISO standard-like) |
   383	| **Performance** | ✓ Pure managed code, inlining friendly |
   384	| **AnyCPU native arm64** | ✓ No platform-specific code |
   385	| **Vendorability** | ✓ Self-contained source file |
   386	
   387	### 8.2 Rationale
   388	
   389	- **Hand-port from C++:** The ms-numpress C++ source is ~400 lines, well-commented, and published. Porting ~150 lines of the core encode/decode logic to C# is straightforward and introduces no external runtime dependency.
   390	- **Avoid NuGet:** No official C# NuGet package exists. A hypothetical numpress-rs via FFI would add complexity (P/Invoke, native library management).
   391	- **Avoid x64 markers:** mzLib (historical) and other .NET ports carry x64-specific baggage. Our hand-port is pure managed C# (AnyCPU).
